<font color="#FF0000">I GOTTA GET AN INTERPRETER</font><br>
<tt>Sun Aug 17 23:17:02 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook,<br>
     I realize others have taken up the cudgels, but I still want to clarify my position.  You make me feel sometimes like I'm speaking ancient Sumerian.  I never said &quot;locals&quot;. Unless I'm very mistaken, the North was extremely well supplied with peasants for the draft.  The leadership up there considered their high birthrate as one of their key military resources.  As for weapons, Chinese 82mm mortars and Russian 122mm guns etc. were all part of the NVA arsenal, but am not aware weapons have ideology.  Were ours democratic weapons?  Gee, I think I'll toss this libertarian grenade here.  I mean, really, please think about it.  It does NOT bother me that you killed Communist soldiers, but that you insist that THEY ALL WERE COMMIES! that rubs me raw.  Just look at our guys.  Tell me, how many different shades of politics and/or religion existed in your squad or platoon at any given point in time?  As for never seeing the enemy, saw prisoners being brought to or from our POW interrogation compound on and off.  Some were local and some were NVA.  Most were a sorry, sullen looking bunch, which was hardly surprising.<br><br>
Concerning the handle &quot;professor&quot;: Tom and Chet thought I should have a nickname.  Gave them 3 out of my past.  &quot;Professor&quot; comes from 7th thru 12th grade.  Also, when serving at Fort Carson after Vietnam was given the following by a field test group I spent 4 months with: &quot;The Encyclopedia Award for Extraneous Information.&quot;  If you don't want to use it, No Problem.  I went without a nickname for over 20 years.  I only have a BS, not More of the Same, or Piled High and Dry, and therefore lack official standing.<br><br>
Concerning Chevys vs. Fords:<br>
     GM = General Maintenance  or  Gummed up Machinery<br>
                            but<br>
     FORD = Fix Or Repair Daily  or Found On Road Dead 
<p><code>-- gerald_ney@icpphil.navy.mil  (Gerald, &quot;professor&quot;, 7/68-7/69) </code><p>


